    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Tax-Cut Plan Vs. Unmet Needs</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Duncan Osborne letter on Aug 26 article comparing Gov George W Bush's tax proposal with Pres Ronald Reagan's tax cuts</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Bush Tax Plan: The Debate Takes Shape'' (front page, Aug. 26) compares George W. Bush's current proposal with President Ronald Reagan's tax cuts. What you do not say is that Mr. Reagan made up the revenue shortfalls his tax cuts created by borrowing billions of dollars. That is Mr. Reagan's real legacy.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Bush Tax Plan: The Debate Takes Shape'' (front page, Aug. 26) compares George W. Bush's current proposal with President Ronald Reagan's tax cuts. What you do not say is that Mr. Reagan made up the revenue shortfalls his tax cuts created by borrowing billions of dollars. That is Mr. Reagan's real legacy.</p>
        <p>What both Mr. Bush and Al Gore need to guarantee is that any tax cuts will not be offset by borrowing that will be a burden of future administrations and taxpayers. What they will do for us now is not enough, especially when today's tax giveback carries a punishing cost years later.</p>
        <p>DUNCAN OSBORNE  Brooklyn, Aug. 26, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
